statement:
A particle is moving in the (x,y)-plane along the curve $y = x^{2}$. As
it passes through the point P = (2, 4), its y coordinate changes at a
rate of 8 units/sec.

ii) What is the rate of change of the particle's distance $D(t)$ to the
origin at this instant?

\begin{figure}[htbp]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=.5\textwidth]{MATH102_2011_7ii.png}
\caption{MATH102 2011 7ii.png}
\end{figure}

sols:
As discussed in the hint,

\begin{align*}\displaystyle D(t)^{2} = x(t)^{2} + y(t)^{2}\end{align*}

Differentiating yields

\begin{align*}\displaystyle 2D(t)\frac{dD}{dt} = 2x\frac{dx}{dt} + 2y\frac{dy}{dt}\end{align*}

From the previous part, we have that

\begin{align*}\displaystyle \frac{dx}{dt}\bigg|_{x=2} = 2\end{align*}

and we are given that

\begin{align*}\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dt}\bigg|_{x=2} = 8\end{align*}

and so plugging in the point $\displaystyle (x(t),y(t)) = (2,4)$, and
$\displaystyle D(t) = \sqrt{x(t)^2+y(t)^2}$ (\emph{D} must be positive)
we have

\begin{align*}
 2\sqrt{x(t)^{2} + y(t)^{2}}\frac{dD}{dt} &=   2D(t)\frac{dD}{dt} = 2x(t)\frac{dx}{dt} + 2y(t)\frac{dy}{dt} \\
 2\sqrt{(2)^{2} + (4)^{2}}\frac{dD}{dt} &=  2(2)(2) + 2(4)(8) \\
 2\sqrt{20} \frac{dD}{dt} &=  72 \\
\frac{dD}{dt} &=  \frac{36}{\sqrt{20}} = \frac{18}{\sqrt{5}} = \frac{18}5 \sqrt{5} \end{align*}

completing the question. All answers in the last line are equivalently
correct.
